@Kaffie: 
> You cannot sell software unless you also provide the source. Thus, it prohibits the use of the software for commercial production.
It is true that you cannot sell the software under GPL without releasing the source, but only at *the point of distribution*. Meaning, they are allowed to only give the source to people who have paid for the product. These people can then do the same thing with the source, or distribute it without a fee, etc. Free doesn't mean it has no price. It means people can modify, distribute, etc. **Under GPL, once the person has bought the software, and therefore gotten the source, they can modify, distribute, etc., including making it paid, and therefore *commercial*.**

@Kaffie: BTW, regarding:
> You cannot, for instance, take GPL licensed code, use it in a commercial product, and then ship that product and sell it.
Red Hat does this with Linux.
